    permitAndLicensePara: "Michigan Department of Licensing and Regulatory Affairs (LARA) issues master and journeyman plumbing licenses. Verify at lara.michigan.gov. Michigan additionally requires Residential Builders license for general contracting. Detroit permits route through Buildings Safety Engineering and Environmental Department (BSEED). Suburban Wayne County communities including Grosse Pointe, Dearborn, and Livonia use their own building departments with varying turnaround. The Michigan Plumbing Code Part 7 applies statewide with local amendments for Detroit's combined-sewer service.",
    stormwaterAndSewerPara: "Detroit's combined sewer backs up during heavy storms, and GLWA's Water Resource Recovery Facility treats the combined flow. The Rouge River and Detroit River watersheds drive regional stormwater attention. The Great Lakes Water Authority Capital Improvement Program invests billions in combined-sewer separation. DWSD Basement Flooding Rebate Program provides $1,000 per property for documented backup-prevention retrofits. The Wayne County Flood and Erosion Control Ordinance governs private-side stormwater in unincorporated areas.",
    waterHeaterCulturePara: "Detroit residential water heaters are predominantly gas tank units at 40 or 50 gallons from AO Smith, Bradford White, or Rheem, supplied by DTE Energy natural gas or Consumers Energy in the metro. Electric heat pump water heaters qualify for DTE Energy Appliance Rebate Program plus federal IRA credits. Tankless Rinnai or Navien condensing units are gaining adoption. The state of Michigan's Low Income Home Energy Assistance Program (LIHEAP) supports weatherization that includes water-heater efficiency improvements.",
    winterizationPara: "Detroit winters bring sustained sub-freezing temperatures from December through February with periodic arctic plunges. The 2014 polar vortex with sub-negative-15 temperatures split pipes and cracked basement walls across Wayne County. The 2019 Wayne County deep freeze produced documented burst-pipe waves. Foam pipe insulation on basement runs plus frost-free Woodford Model 17 hose bibs are standard retrofits. Heat tape with GFCI protection wraps exposed service lines. Michigan Residential Code requires foundation insulation and air sealing that reduces pipe-freeze risk.",
    emergencyRepairPara: "Emergency plumbing in Detroit runs 2 to 2.5 times scheduled rates with peaks during January polar vortex events. Companies like Waterwork Plumbing, Roto-Rooter Detroit, and Benjamin Franklin Plumbing Detroit operate 24/7 citywide. Response times extend during sustained cold snaps. Michigan LARA license verification at lara.michigan.gov catches out-of-state operators. Detroit BSEED contractor registration required for city work. The Michigan Attorney General's Consumer Protection Division tracks home-improvement fraud and prosecutes unlicensed operators.",
    wellAndSepticPara: "Detroit city limits have no wells or septic. Outlying Wayne, Oakland, Macomb, and Washtenaw County communities use wells tested through Michigan Department of Environment Great Lakes and Energy (EGLE) and septic systems regulated by county health departments under Michigan Public Act 451. Aerobic Treatment Units are common on tight-soil lots. Septic-to-sewer conversion in gentrifying suburbs runs $10,000 to $25,000. Macomb County Environmental Health and Oakland County Health Division handle separate permit portals for suburban work.",
    commonIssuesPara: "The dominant Detroit residential plumbing issue is combined-sewer backups during heavy rain events that force water through basement floor drains. Lead service lines persist on pre-1986 stock. Aging galvanized in 1920s-1940s Indian Village and Boston Edison homes. Freeze-burst pipes during January-February polar vortex events. Detroit Land Bank parcel work reveals undocumented-fill issues from prior demolitions. Tree root intrusion in East English Village and Morningside clay-tile laterals. DWSD basement flooding rebate claims document recurring problem properties.",
